summary: [INC000020691067] Job Scheduler Does Not Handle the Case Where a Device in a Job Moves Sites
description: The scheduled service bus message that triggers a job contains a list of devices in it.  When a job exists for a site, but then a device moves out of that site, the list of devices in the job’s service bus message never gets updated, so the job continues to operate on the moved device.

summary: [INC000020670311] Handle Case where DeviceModifiedEvent has no Path
description:
We see exceptions thrown by the Aggregator when it processes Device Modified Events that do not have a Path (There are many) 

Existing code tries to parse the path of the device that has been modified to get the GatewayId for it and throws an exception if there is no path to parse. 

New code will look up the path using the service comm library if the path is not in the event.

related_issues.summary: INC000020670311- Entitlement Aggregator failed to process Eda Device Modified event.

description:
A number of calls to this endpoint take about 20 seconds, but most calls are subsecond.  We need to understand where the bottleneck is.  I looked in logs and we don't currently have enough logging to know where in the flow the delay is.  In general there are 3 potential places:

* Get user record from memory cache/Mongo. I'd think for a service account that this would be cached, but would be good to know how long this takes.
* Call Okta to get the token
* Persist a hash of the token to Cosmos

The work in this bug will add logging to those 3 places that will log if any of them take > 1 second
